contributing 55% and 45% to the total amplitude, respectively, and to a single-exponential function with kobs ϭ 0.0052 sϪ1 in the case of retro all-D a-p5ЈЈ. The reaction traces of the retro all-D peptide and the normal
all-D were normalized to the same total amplitude. The reaction of retro
all-D p5Ј-a could also be fitted to a single-exponential function with kobs ϭ 0.0058 sϪ1 (not shown). Inset, corresponding spectra of normal all-D a-p5Ј (OO) and retro all-D a-p5ЈЈ(ϩ) before and after addition of DnaJ. For details of the fluorescence measurements, see “Experimental
Procedures.”

RESULTS AND DISCUSSION
Binding of Acrylodan-labeled D-Peptides to DnaJ—The labeled peptide a-p5 (CLLLSAPRR), which represents part of the presequence of mitochondrial aspartate aminotransferase, has previously been shown to bind to both DnaK and DnaJ, with Kd values of 0.06 ␮M and 37 ␮M, respectively (7). The similar all-L peptide a-p5Ј (CALLLSAARR), which binds to DnaK with a Kd of 0.1 ␮M (not shown), was used as reference peptide in this study. Addition of DnaJ to normal all-D a-p5Ј and retro all-D a-p5ЈЈ (for the structures of the peptides, see Table I) resulted in an increase in fluorescence and a shift in the emission maximum from 526 nm to 520 nm, indicating binding of these peptides (Fig. 1). Similar binding-induced changes in fluorescence were observed with all-L a-p5 and all-L a-p5Ј (Table I), suggesting that the acrylodan-labels of DnaJ-bound normal all-D a-p5Ј and retro all-D a-p5ЈЈ are located in an environment similar to that of the DnaJ-bound all-L peptides. In contrast, addition of DnaJ to retro all-D p5Ј-a, which has the fluorophore attached to its C-term, shifted the fluorescence maximum to 490 nm. This more pronounced blue shift (Fig. 2) is an exception among all peptides tested and suggests that the acrylodan label of retro all-D p5Ј-a is situated at the opposite site of the peptide-binding region of DnaJ (Table I). This interpretation implies that retro all-D p5Ј-a, as the other tested D-peptides, binds with the same peptide backbone direction as the L-peptides. All-L and normal all-D peptides were bound in a biphasic process, while the binding of both retro all-D peptides could be

FIG. 2. Fluorescence titration of the acrylodan-labeled retro all-D p5؅ with DnaJ. Retro all-D p5Ј-a (50 nm) in assay buffer (— — —) was titrated with increasing concentrations of DnaJ, and emission spectra were recorded after reaching equilibrium (OO). Inset, the titration curve was obtained by plotting the differences in fluorescence at 490 nm against the total DnaJ concentration and fitting these data points to the following nonlinear regression equation: ⌬F ϭ (⌬Fmax/2 ϫ Lt) ϫ {(Lt ϩ Pt ϩ Kd) Ϫ [(Lt ϩ Pt ϩ Kd)2 Ϫ(4 ϫ Lt ϫ Pt)]0.5}, where ⌬F is the change in relative fluorescence, Lt is the total concentration of acrylodan-labeled peptide, and Pt is the total concentration of DnaJ. The calculated value of Kd was 0.9 ␮M.
fitted to single-exponential functions (Fig. 1). The two retro all-D peptides are the most strongly binding ligands; normal all-D a-p5Ј binds with lower affinity, similar to that of all-L a-p5Ј (Table I). For comparison, the 17-residue N-terminal peptide of rhodanese has been reported to bind with a Kd Ͻ 20 nM to DnaJ but not to DnaK (23). We used this high affinity peptide ligand to check the specificity of binding of the tested D-peptides. Addition of 4 ␮M unlabeled rhodanese peptide to preformed complexes of normal all-D a-p5Ј and retro all-D p5Ј-a with DnaJ (conditions as described in the legend to Fig. 1, except that 1.5 ␮M DnaJ was used) decreased the fluorescence signal of the DnaJ-bound labeled peptides in a time-dependent

