process (not shown); however, for yet unknown reasons, the fluorescence signal was not abolished completely. Apparently, the rhodanese peptide and the D-peptides bind at least in part to the same site. The hydrophobic acrylodan label itself seems to contribute only little to the binding; the Kd value of acrylodan-labeled 2-mercaptoethanol proved to be Ͼ 800 ␮M.3
Competition of Binding of all-L Peptide to DnaJ—To confirm that the D-analogs were bound to the same binding site as the L-peptides, we performed competition experiments in which unlabeled normal all-D p5Ј and retro all-D p5Ј competed with 50 nM labeled reference peptide all-L a-p5Ј for binding to DnaJ (Fig. 3). The IC50 value, i.e. the concentration at which the D-peptides inhibited binding of a-p5Ј to 50%, was 0.6 ␮M and 2.2 ␮M for the retro all-D and the normal all-D peptide, respectively. The Ki values were calculated, assuming competitive inhibition, with Equation 1 (24, 25)

